Description: Intact pottery vessel with a flat base and flat-topped rim. Probably made of coarse red silt clay, the vessel has a projecting boss of clay attached to the interior wall, and opposite this there is a small hole through the wall of the vessel.
Excavator/field collector: Excavated by: Dr David George Hogarth
Findspot: Excavated/Findspot: Great Temenos, Vicinity (outside) of the north-west corner (Hogarth excavations 1903)
Curator's comments: Excavated from the area of the north-west corner of the 'Great Temenos' by Hogarth in 1903. dated by Edgar to the 7th to 5th century BC, but probably 'nearer the earlier limitit', and he cites Saite parallels (Edgar 1905, 125, Fig.5).

Another example from Naukratis: GR 1974,1119.1. Parallels from Tell Dafana, Petrie, W.M.F., Tanis II, Nebesheh and Defenneh, London, 1888, pl.xxxiv, no.26; Boston MFA 87.637. Other parallels: Petrie 1915, Hyksos and Israelite Cities, pl. x, no. 5; 1988, ‘Tell Fara’on-Imet’, BCE 13, 20–1, fig. 3
Bibliographic references: Villing et al 2013-2015 / Naukratis: Greeks in Egypt (IB.040) (Phase 3)
